John Edward: language skills are a key skill for global citizens
Learning outcomes in private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has continued in 2018 as a result of good test scores, boosted by individual and community success in sport, art, music and other community-based initiatives.
These schools of more than 30,000 pupils, represented by SCIS, Scotland's Council of Private Schools, aim to provide a high level of service to their pupils as well as to the parents of pupils.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for careers of their choice, post-graduate and higher education, and global citizenship.
As an operator in the field of education, who can design and implement tailored study contents, we have noticed the status of languages as a popular and desirable subject in educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his or her own language, the message goes to his or her heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English language if we want to build relationships of trust with people in other countries.
This year’s latest test results show that languages are at the top of the list in terms of pass rates among private schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data was collected from 74 schools belonging to SCIS and showed that 72% of the students who received the best grade were studying Mandarin, 72% were studying German, 69% were studying French and 63% were studying Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the learning of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are valued in the same way as natural sciences (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the private school curriculum and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment Office in 2014 revealed that 17 per cent of the situations where employers had difficulty finding a suitable employee were explained by insufficient language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary in order to promote the future career development of young people.
The more language skills are required for possible tasks, the more relevant these skills become in the global world.
If a person has learned a second language, they will have an advantage in the future over this lifelong skill, regardless of which career they have chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a person with language skills ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey, 75 percent of more than 4,000 UK adults are unable to converse in a foreign language, with French being the only language spoken by 15 percent of the population.
That’s why investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Knowledge of the languages of developing countries, in particular, gives children a better chance of finding a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are expected to be important to British people in 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, private schools always have several language options taught by specialized teachers.
Private schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in an international business environmentlanguages will continue to be of great importance for the country’s future, so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should indeed be seen as 'international communication skills'.
Private schools will continue to provide this freedom of choice, diversity and high level for young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of SCIS, Scotland's Council of Private Schools.
