"However, we have not seen a similar gesture from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, we cannot be sure that national security will be maintained, so under these circumstances it is not possible to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri echoed the well-known lamentation that Washington would not accept a phased denuclearization, where North Korea would be rewarded for each milestone, his statement is nonetheless significant in the sense that unilateral disarmament was not completely excluded, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first U.S.-North Korea summit in Singapore on June 12th. In the statement, Kim asserted “the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea tried to officially end the Korean War of 1950–53, but the United States insisted that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also opposed easing tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States demands ‘nuclear disarmament first,’ and has increased the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goals by force — even opposing the ‘proclamation of peace,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions will bring us to our knees is the dream of the indifferent.
But the problem is that continued sanctions only deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans to hold the next Kim-Trump summit, which Trump himself highlighted to the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings with South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If the party calling for disarmament were South Korea and not the United States, the situation would not have reached such an impasse."
Yet Rin’s tone was markedly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that missiles aimed at the continental United States were inevitable after the “evil president” Trump called Kim a “missile man” with suicidal intentions.
Just last year, Trump threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, but this year Trump praised Kim for his courage to approach disarmament, but stressed that there is still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea abandons nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time limit: “If it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia have suggested that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the progress it has already made.
