Harvard students take a course to get enough rest
All undergraduate students at Harvard University attend a course this year designed to increase student rest. The course is a backlash to the university’s thriving macho culture, where students spend a long night with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, the students of the best university in the world are often quite ignorant of the basic issues related to their own well-being.
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, believes the course will be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler came up with the idea for the course after lecturing on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing about this now, in my last year of study?’
No one had ever told him about the need for sleep, which I was surprised,” he told The Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how correct sleep patterns support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor at Harvard Medical School and vice president of the university’s health services, said the university decided to hold a course after hearing about students suffering severe sleep deprivation during the study week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are shown a picture of a dormitory room where they can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
With interactive icons, the campus map encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
"We know that this does not have a direct impact on student behavior.
We believe, however, that they have a right to know about these issues in exactly the same way that they have a right to know about the health effects of smoking," adds Professor Czeisler.
According to Professor Czeisler, all-night study marathons are still a source of pride, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures on students made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
“Adequate and quality sleep should be a student’s ‘secret weapon’ against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a brain state that resembles starvation, which is why people are constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology in California, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
She says that the course opened her eyes and gave her the impetus to organise a course that would cover all the students on the campus.
He hopes that all doctoral students could complete a similar course of study before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning, as well as reminding them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic displays and “blue light” from LED lighting on circadian rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
