New Cancer Vaccine Can Teach Immune System to ‘See’ Malignant Cells
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and destroy them
Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Malignant Cells as Part of Treatment
The method involves isolating resistant cells from the patient and modifying them in the laboratory
After treatment, the cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the proteins typical of many cancers
The test vaccine has shown promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
For example, the cancer cells of a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months of being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method involves isolating resistant cells from the patient and modifying them in the laboratory so that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of many cancers. The modified cells are then injected back into the body.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: “Based on our results, it is a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of several types of cancer," explains Professor Berzofsky. "These include breast cancer as well as ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach —taking resistant cells from a patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells— has also been successful in treating one type of leukemia.
