Launched in 2012, the Global Citizen Festival is a follow-up to the Global Powerty Project, an international advisory group that aims to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively working to eradicate it.
In order to get a free ticket to an event (unless you are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), the public must perform various tasks or “acts”, such as volunteering, sending an email to a political decision-maker or making a phone call, or performing some other act that spreads awareness of the project’s goals.
But how has Global Citizen been successful, now that we only have 12 years to reach our goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert ticket a real way to persuade them to take action, or is it just another ‘clickivism’ among others – the idea that you can change the world by signing an online address or sending a tweet?
Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million “actions” for different purposes since 2011.
These actions have encouraged policymakers to announce commitments and principles equivalent to more than $37 billion, and have been used in ways that will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group listed 390 commitments and statements on the basis of which more than $10 billion has already been spent or collected.
The group estimates that the funds reached have already affected the lives of nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based group of investors and executors committed to “helping children develop to their full potential.” The group committed to providing Rwanda with $35 million to end malnutrition in the country, after activists sent them 4,700 tweets as a result of the Global Citizen campaign.
“Thanks to the British government, donors, governments of different countries, and global citizens just like you, we can put social injustice and malnutrition in the history of the press,” Tracey Ullman, the ambassador for Power of Nutrition, told the audience at a concert in London in 2018.
The group also called on the British government to take action to improve the nutrition of mothers and children through more than 5,000 actions. The government has announced funding for the Power on Nutrition project, which focuses on fighting malnutrition and reaches 5 million mothers and children.
One of the most frequently asked questions on the movement’s website is, “Why do you think we can end extreme poverty?”
Global citizen’s answer: “The road will be long and difficult and there are many stumbling blocks ahead.
But we will succeed, like the great civil rights struggles and anti-apartheid movements before us, because together we are stronger.”
